Hi Colin,

Are you sure this network as learned XOR, and not the
particular sequence of inputs?

Is the network memory flushed out before the next
input is fed into it?  Have you tried shuffling the
order of the input and gotten the same responses?

Ken&#39;s right...technically you should disable
recurrency when attempting to solve XOR.  But if this
network isn&#39;t memorizing the sequence, then I&#39;d agree
that it is interesting. :)

Derek

--- Colin Green &lt;cgreen@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Take a look at this network that performs logical
&gt; XOR...
&gt; 
&gt; ------------------------------------------------
&gt;     neuron id=&quot;0&quot; type=&quot;bias&quot;
&gt;     neuron id=&quot;1&quot; type=&quot;in&quot;
&gt;     neuron id=&quot;2&quot; type=&quot;in&quot;
&gt;     neuron id=&quot;3&quot; type=&quot;out&quot;
&gt; 
&gt;     connection src-id=&quot;0&quot; tgt-id=&quot;3&quot;
&gt; weight=&quot;1.64327624043105&quot;
&gt;     connection src-id=&quot;1&quot; tgt-id=&quot;3&quot;
&gt; weight=&quot;-3.3017311279049&quot;
&gt;     connection src-id=&quot;2&quot; tgt-id=&quot;3&quot;
&gt; weight=&quot;-3.3025163810043&quot;
&gt;     connection src-id=&quot;3&quot; tgt-id=&quot;3&quot;
&gt; weight=&quot;-7.44947553716588&quot;
&gt; ------------------------------------------------
&gt; 
&gt; Activate Fn is
&gt; (1.0D/(1.0D+(Math.Exp(-accumulator))))   - this has 
&gt; continuous output of 0.0 to 1.0
&gt; 
&gt; It surprised me because I was expecting at least 1
&gt; hidden node - the 
&gt; textbook example I have been using for tests has 2.
&gt; 
&gt; The truth table for the network looks like this:
&gt; 
&gt; 0    1    2    3(t0)    3(t1)
&gt; --------------------------
&gt; 1    0    0    0.83     0.01
&gt; 1    0    1    0.16     0.05
&gt; 1    1    0    0.16     0.05
&gt; 1    1    1    0.007    0.007
&gt; 
&gt; Admitedly the seperation between true and false is
&gt; small, but it&#39;s 
&gt; there. From this we can see that the non-linearity
&gt; introduced by the 
&gt; feedback on the output node plays a crucial part. So
&gt; although there are 
&gt; no hidden nodes, for practical purposes the output
&gt; node is performing 
&gt; the role of a hidden node.
&gt; 
&gt; Just though i&#39;d mention it as a nice small example
&gt; of how an evolution 
&gt; based search has found an unexpected (to me anyway!)
&gt; architecture.
&gt; 
&gt; Colin.
